    <sec sec-type="intro">
      <title>INTRODUCTION</title>
      <p>Squamoid eccrine ductal carcinoma (SEDC) is an extremely rare subtype of eccrine
carcinoma (EC): only twelve cases were reported in the literature to date (<xref ref-type="table" rid="t1">Table 1</xref>).<sup><xref rid="r1" ref-type="bibr">1</xref></sup> Due to the rarity of this tumor and to the difficulty of its
histopathologic diagnosis, almost half of the cases are incorrectly diagnosed as
squamous cell carcinoma (SCC) in the initial biopsy.<sup><xref rid="r2" ref-type="bibr">2</xref></sup> The origin of lesion is controversial, as it may
represent a SCC emerging from eccrine duct, an EC subtype with extensive squamous
differentiation or a biphenotypic carcinoma.<sup><xref rid="r1" ref-type="bibr">1</xref></sup> We report the thirteenth case of SEDC in the literature,
whose diagnosis was possible in the incisional biopsy.</p>
